'''Burtas''' ({{lang-ru|Буртасы}}, ''Burtasy''; {{lang-cv|Пăртассем}}, ''Părtassem''; {{lang-tt|Бортаслар|Bortaslar|برطاسلر or بۇرتاسلار}}) were a tribe of uncertain ethnolinguistic affiliation inhabiting the [[steppe]] region north of the [[Caspian Sea]] in medieval times (modern [[Penza Oblast]], [[Ulyanovsk Oblast]] and [[Saratov Oblast]] of the [[Russia| Russian Federation]]). They were subject to the [[Khazars]].

The ethnic identity of the Burtas is disputed, with several different theories ranging from them being a [[Uralic languages|Uralic]] tribal confederacy (probably later assimilated to Turkic language), and therefore perhaps the ancestors of the modern [[Mokshas|Moksha people]], or that they were an [[Iranic]] tribe, possibly the ancestors of the modern [[Mishars]].

Recently, some scholars have suggested that the Burtas were actually [[Alans]] or another [[Iranian peoples|Iranian]] ethnolinguistic group. The Alanic ([[Sarmatian]]) origin is also derived from their name furt/fort (big river on [[Middle Iranian languages|Middle Iranian language]])  and [[Alans|''as'']] is Alanic selfname, as [[Ossetians]] (Caucasian [[Alans]]) and [[Jassic people|Jasses]] ([[Jasz people|Jasz]], Hungarian [[Alans]]) all used the same name.

