{{Infobox ethnic group | group = Jaegaseung | native_name = 재가승 | native_name_lang = ko | image = | image_caption = | total = <!-- total population worldwide --> | total_year = <!-- year of total population --> | total_source = <!-- source of total population; may be ''census'' or ''estimate'' --> | total_ref = <!-- references supporting total population --> | genealogy = | regions = Northeast Asian | languages = Variety of [[Ryukjin dialect]] of Korean language | religions = Buddhism
| related_groups = [[Jurchen]], [[Koreans]] | footnotes = }} {{Use mdy dates|date=April 2016}} [[File:Jaegaseung temple.jpg|thumb|A Buddhist temple built by Korean Jaegaseung minority]] [[File:Jaegaseung yellow oatmeal paper.jpg|thumb|An example of [[oatmeal paper]] traditionally produced by Jaegaseung minority in Korea]]
'''Jaegaseung''' ({{korean|context=north|hangul = 재가승}}, {{lang-ja|在家僧}}) were [[Jurchen people]] descendants who live in Korea. They formed villages of married lay monks.<ref name="LA_lecture"/> They produced [[oatmeal paper]] and substituted their tax with it.<ref>[http://newslibrary.naver.com/viewer/index.nhn?articleId=1936010100209251001&edtNo=1&printCount=1&publishDate=1936-01-01&officeId=00020&pageNo=51&printNo=5421&publishType=00020 Dong-A ilbo], January 1, 1936, 51th page</ref> In modern times, Jaegaseung people were [[Cultural assimilation|assimilated]] to [[Koreans|Korean people]] by [[North Korea]].<ref name="Hwansoo"/> Their villages existed from the 18th century, when their descendants migrated from China, to the 1960s.<ref name="LA_lecture">{{citeweb|url=http://buddhistartnews.wordpress.com/2013/04/17/los-angeles-lecture-koreas-jodoshinshu-lay-monk-villages-in-colonial-korea-25-april-2013/|title=Los Angeles Lecture: Korea’s Jōdōshinshū: Lay Monk Villages in Colonial Korea (25 April 2013)|date=April 25, 2013|access-date=April 25, 2016}}</ref>
Monastic identity of the lay monks was seen as [[antisocialism|antisocialist]], and the villages have ceased to exist.<ref name="Hwansoo">{{cite journal |author=Kim Hwansoo|date=2013|title='The Mystery of the Century:' Lay Buddhist Monk Villages (Chaegasŭngch'on) Near Korea's Northernmost Border, 1600s–1960|url=http://s-space.snu.ac.kr/bitstream/10371/93058/1/02.pdf |journal=Seoul Journal of Korean Studies|volume=26|issue=2|pages=297–299|access-date=April 24, 2016}}</ref>
Buddhist communities have been repressed by communist governments in Asian countries. The local communities had survived through [[Korea under Japanese rule|colonial period]] without serious pressure from outside.<ref name="ReynoldsCarbine2000">{{cite book|author1=Frank Reynolds|author2=Jason A. Carbine|title=The Life of Buddhism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OnjDUqgFvToC&pg=PA16|year=2000|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-21105-6|page=16}}</ref>
