{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}} {{Infobox organization |name= Nigerian Academy of Letters |image = |alt = <!-- alt text; see [[WP:ALT]] --> |caption = |map = <!-- optional --> |motto = |formation = {{Start date and years ago|df=yes|1974|07|17}} |extinction = <!-- date of extinction, optional --> |type= Autonomous [[learned society]] |status = A [[national academy]] |purpose = Promotion of scholarship and research in Humanities |headquarters = NAL Secretariat |coords = <!-- Coordinates of location using a coordinates template --> |language = [[English language|English]] |leader_title = President |leader_name = Professor [[Olu Obafemi]] |main_organ = |parent_organization = <!-- if one --> |affiliations = <!-- if any --> |budget = |remarks = |image_border = |size = <!-- default 200 --> |msize = <!-- map size, optional, default 200px --> |malt = <!-- map alt text --> |mcaption = <!-- optional --> |abbreviation =NAL |location =[[Abuja]], [[Nigeria]] |region_served = Worldwide |membership = 84 Fellows |num_staff = |num_volunteers = |website ={{official|http://nal.org.ng/}} }} The '''Nigerian Academy of Letters''' is a [[national academy]] and apex body of arts and literature in Nigeria. It is an autonomous, [[scholarly]] and non-political state institution for advancing scholarship and public interest in the humanities at the highest level in Nigeria. Established in 1974 after recommendation of ''"Udoji report of 1974"'' it is currently governed by executive committee of distinguished professors and promote limited number of four types of fellows; Foundation Fellows, Regular Fellows, Overseas Fellows and Honorary Fellows on a yearly basis.
There are currently 84 Fellows in the Academy; 7 foundation fellows, 51 regular fellows, 12 overseas fellows and 14 honorary fellows.<ref name="Fellows">{{cite web|url=http://nal.org.ng/fellows|title=Our Fellows|publisher=Nigerian Academy of Letters|accessdate=13 January 2018}}</ref>
== History == The Academy was established in 1974 after a governmental report ''Udoji Report of 1974'' made a recommendation for the creation of national academies.<ref name="NICI">{{cite web|url=http://www.nico.gov.ng/index.php/category-list/906-nigerian-academy-of-letters-holds-15th-annual-convocation|title=Nigerian Academy Of Letters Holds 15th Annual Convocation|publisher=National Institute for Cultural Orientation|date=12 August 2013|accessdate=13 January 2018}}</ref>
== Fellowship == There are four types of fellows in the Nigerian Academy of Letters: Foundation Fellows, Regular Fellows (normally resident in Nigeria), Overseas Fellows (resident abroad) and Honorary Fellows.<ref name="UI">{{cite web|url=https://www.unilorin.edu.ng/index.php/en/communication-and-information-sciences/237-unilorinnews/4047-unilorin-staff-members-tasked-on-fitness-exercise|title=Guidelines for the Nomination of Fellows |publisher=[[University of Ilorin]]|date=|accessdate=13 January 2018}}</ref> Fellows are appointed for life and every prospective fellow must be nominated by a living Fellow. Self-nomination is forbidden.<ref name="UI"/> The Fellowship is given rarely to distinguished professors after a rigorous election exercise. Not more than two candidates from any discipline and not more than four in any one year can be admitted into the Academy. Elected Fellows are inducted at an investiture ceremony, which formally confers on them the right to use the [[postnominal]] Fellow of the Nigerian Academy of Letters (FNAL).<ref name="Laurels">{{cite web|url=https://www.dailytrust.com.ng/news/others/laurels-by-the-nigerian-academy-of-letters/14783.html|title=Laurels by the Nigerian Academy of Letters|work=[[Daily Trust]]|author=Olu Obafemi|date=14 September 2013|accessdate=13 January 2018}}</ref> === Foundation Fellows === Foundation Fellowship is static, non elected body of Nigerian scholars who are the founding members of the Academy. * Professor Emeritus [[Ayo Bamgbose]], [[NNOM]] ( Foundation President) * Professor Emeritus [[J. F. Ade Ajayi]] NNOM * Professor Emeritus [[Adiele Afigbo]], NNOM * Professor Emeritus [[Adeboye Babalola]], NNOM * Professor [[Chinua Achebe]], NNOM * Professors [[J. P. Clark-Bekederemo]], NNOM * Professor [[Wole Soyinka]], [[Nobel Prize|Nobel]] Laureate
