{{Quote box||quoted=true |title = ''The Indictment of Walter atte Keye'', November 1381|salign=center|width=25em||source=– [[The National Archives]], ''coram rege'' rolls: KB 27/482/43|quote=...Walter atte Keye, leading a company of other malefactors, came to the house of Andrew Vernoun, brewer, at Paul's Wharf, London, on the said Friday [14 June]. Walter criminally and treasonably forced his way into the said house unless the latter paid a fine to him. In the face of these threats, and in fear of his life, Andrew paid a fine of 3s 4''d'' which Walter received despite its criinal and treasonable form. Accordngly Walter was a common malefactor to take such fines, as he did with many men in the said city of London.{{sfn|Dobson|1983|p=227}}}} 
'''Walter atte Keye''' was a late-fourteenth-century [[brewer]] and [[tailor]] from [[Sheffield]]. He is best known as one of the leaders of the 1381 [[Peasants' Revolt]] in London.

On 14 June 1381{{sfn|Petit-Dutaillis|Lefebvre|1969|p=282 n.3}} Keye attempted to steal and destroy the [[Court of Common Council|Common Council]]'s book of [[By-law|ordinances]], called ''le Jubyle'', or Jubilee Book.{{refn|The Jubilee Book (so-called due to is compilation during Edward III's jubilee year, 1376-7), substantially and radically revised the city's [[By-law|ordinances]], although due to its later destruction by Mayor Exton, the book's precise contents remain necessarily vague.{{sfn|Barron|1981|p=16}}|group=note}} It was stored in a [[sheriff]]'s [[compter]]. The rebels also attacked the [[Guildhall]] and other civic buildings first{{sfn|Barker|2014|p=276}} and at least the former he attempted to burn down.{{sfn|Petit-Dutaillis|Lefebvre|1969|p=282 n.3}} Since the book was subsequently burned by a later Mayor of London, [[Nicholas Exton]],{{sfn|Turner|2007|p=21}} little is known of its contents of the book.  Historians have been unable to ascertain Keye's motive for his "frenzied" search for it.{{sfn|Dobson|1983|p=227}}{{sfn|London|1907|p=lii}} Keye also appears to have personally led a small armed force to the Milk Street [[sheriff]]'s [[compter]], which they assaulted and despoiled.{{sfn|Arner|2013|p=39}} Keye also took advantage of the general turmoil of the time to extort money from fellow brewers.{{sfn|Barker|2014|p=276}} He and his associates have been described by [[Barrie Dobson]] as showing that there was at least one rebel group "prepared to challenge the authority of the civic hierarchy as well as that of royal officials and agents."{{sfn|Dobson|1983|pp=226-227}}

